snippet.textDisplay:
I must say, i dont like the new design tough, for some reasons. First of all, it look is again futuristic, like the base design of the PS4, that is nice, im not gonna lie.
But when it comes to aestetics and ergonomics, its questionable wether its size, shape and haptic/grip is right enough to fit in the different hand sizes of people, who havent got a basketball player sized hand (or a regular one). That was the main reason why many people didnt like the design of the PS4 controller, because its stick alignment and spacing between the buttons and triggers were a bit too much or lets say wrong (note: again, this is a major issue for people with smaller hands). Second of all, the light bar. Still, this consumes more energy than a device without any LED dots/stripes of that size, but i must admit they made it very thin this time, so we will see how the battery will handle it at all after the console has been released.


Theres another aspect i want to point out that i find interesting: they kept the trackpad! Once you know how smooth typing via onscreen keyboard with that thing is, you wont miss it. Also scrolling is very intuitive and responsive overall and you can use it via steam on your PC desktop if you like, so its nice to see that the legacy continues with the PS5. :)

snippet.textDisplay: I just hope the build quality of this controller is sturdier than the PS4 controller. I grip my controller when I use one hard, always have, and I never really notice it, so the plastic on the PS4 controllers always broke. I probably paid more for controllers than I did for the console, so I eventually bit the bullet and bought an XB1 Elite controller. I liked the 360 controller but the XB1 controller is a fucking brick with buttons on it, and I can tell the sticks and triggers are more responsive on PS4 controllers over XB1 controllers. So I really hope that the plastic on it isn’t cheap shit (I’d love if they’d sell a metal or alloy one at some point, something that’d still be light but I wouldn’t somehow break just by holding it)

snippet.textDisplay: “Sony said it has been tested on a wide variety,” like ya, no crap. The ergonomics of that design have been put to the test since the XBox 360. It’s pretty smart of Sony: use the exact same controller for PlayStation 1-4 and occasionally add some bits to it like a button, all the while letting XBox do the R&D into ergonomics; hear that all consumers (even PS fanboys) love XBox’s controller design better, and then just copy that shit. I have no side in the console war; before I went to PC, I always had both. I’m just saying it’s a little smart of Sony to rip off XBox R&D but a little BS that they’re trying to pass it off as their own original design.
